<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-445-535  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 445 535.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computers in Banking  Sept 1990 v7 n9 p20(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Relational data bases lift banks' profit.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Zimmerman, Kim Ann.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Banks using relational databases are improving their after-taxprofit by an average of $18.8 million per year, according to areport from market research firm Business Science InternationalInc (BSI).andP;  While businesses traditionally use new technologies toreduce overhead or cut payroll costs, banks use relationaldatabases to boost profits and increase revenues.andP;  Bankerssurveyed say they plan to increase usage of relational databasesin the next two to three years and anticipate an increase inprofit before taxes of an average of $36.5 million a year.andP;  Commonapplications of relational databases include profitabilityanalysis and credit risk analysis.andP;  One bank reports usingrelational databases to target customers who are are likely to beinterested in a new product.andP;  Another used the technology toidentify customers who were using certain combinations ofservices.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Business Science Research International Inc. (reports).andO;Topic:     Relational Data BasesBankingProfit AnalysisReportsBusiness Planning.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>